==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thrust
<hw>Thrust</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>Thrist.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thrust
<hw>Thrust</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Thrust</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Thrusting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets><?/rusten</ets>,
<ets><?/risten</ets>, <ets><?/resten</ets>, Icel.
<ets><?/r<?/st<?/</ets> to thrust, press, force, compel; perhaps akin to
E. <ets>threat</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To push or drive with
force; to drive, force, or impel; to shove; <as>as, to <ex>thrust</ex>
anything with the hand or foot, or with an instrument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Into a dungeon <qex>thrust</qex>, to work with slaves.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stab; to pierce; -- usually with
<xex>through</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To thrust away</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
thrust from</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to push away; to reject.</cd> --
<col><b>To thrust in</b></col>, <cd>to push or drive in.</cd> --
<col><b>To thrust off</b></col>, <cd>to push away.</cd> -- <col><b>To
thrust on</b></col>, <cd>to impel; to urge.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To
thrust one's self in</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To thrust one's self
into</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to obtrude upon, to intrude, as into a room;
to enter (a place) where one is not invited or not welcome.</cd> --
<col><b>To thrust out</b></col>, <cd>to drive out or away; to
expel.</cd> -- <col><b>To thrust through</b></col>, <cd>to pierce; to
stab.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I am eight times <xex>thrust through</xex> the
doublet.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To thrust together</b></col>,
<cd>to compress.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thrust
<hw>Thrust</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a push; to
attack with a pointed weapon; <as>as, a fencer <ex>thrusts</ex> at his
antagonist</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enter by pushing; to squeeze in.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>thrust</qex> between my father and the god.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To push forward; to come with force; to press on; to
intrude.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Young, old, <xex>thrust</xex> there in mighty
concourse.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To thrust to</b></col>, <cd>to rush upon.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As doth an eager hound⟦br⟧
<qex>Thrust to</qex> an hind within some covert glade.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Thrust
<hw>Thrust</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A violent push or
driving, as with a pointed weapon moved in the direction of its length,
or with the hand or foot, or with any instrument; a stab; -- a word much
used as a term of fencing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Polites] Pyrrhus with his lance pursues,⟦br⟧
And often reaches, and his <qex>thrusts</qex> renews.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An attack; an assault.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One <qex>thrust</qex> at your pure, pretended mechanism.</q>
<rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The force or pressure of one part
of a construction against other parts; especially <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, a
horizontal or diagonal outward pressure, as of an arch against its
abutments, or of rafters against the wall which support them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The breaking down of the roof of
a gallery under its superincumbent weight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thrust bearing</b></col> <fld>(Screw Steamers)</fld>,
<cd>a bearing arranged to receive the thrust or endwise pressure of the
screw shaft.</cd> -- <col><b>Thrust plane</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>,
<cd>the surface along which dislocation has taken place in the case of a
reversed fault.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Push; shove; assault; attack.</syn> <usage>
<er>Thrust</er>, <er>Push</er>, <er>Shove</er>. <xex>Push</xex> and
<xex>shove</xex> usually imply the application of force by a body
already in contact with the body to be impelled. <xex>Thrust</xex>,
often, but not always, implies the impulse or application of force by a
body which is in motion before it reaches the body to be
impelled.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thruster</ent>⟦br⟧
